observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the Municipal Planning and Development Office, Municipal Engineering Office, in coordination with the Bids and Awards Committee to:

Conduct a thorough planning for the implementation of development projects by clearly identifying the project procurement timelines as laid down in the Project Procurement Management Plan and Annual Procurement Plan or their equivalent;

Consider the appropriate timing and phasing of the development projects’ implementation taking into account the constraints brought about by the weather conditions; 

Review the guidelines in the conduct of Early Procurement Activities (EPA) for consideration to minimize the delay in the procurement timelines; and

Supervise and monitor the effective and efficient implementation of the project under the 20% development fund so that the necessary and timely intervention can be made to ensure their completion to achieve the objectives in providing socio-economic benefits to the intended beneficiaries.

We recommended and reiterated following courses of action:
All department heads concerned are enjoined to monitor the implementation of all projects funded by other national government agencies, particularly those programs and activities relating to their respective offices in order to achieve the ultimate goals and objectives of the fund which is to promote general welfare and provide basic services to the constituents;
Require the Municipal Account to prepare complete subsidiary ledgers of all fund transfers received;
Require the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to reconcile the balances of Due to NGAs per Subsidiary Ledgers and Utilization Report in order to establish the correct balance of Due to NGAs account in the financial statements of the Municipal Government; and
Immediately return to the source agencies all unused/unutilized balance relating to the fund transfers received from national government agencies especially those that have remained long outstanding.

Based on the above observations, we recommended the Management the following:
Require the Inventory Committee to perform a complete physical count covering all classes of properties owned and controlled by the Municipality using the prescribed report format;
Reconcile the accounting and inventory records in coordination with the Municipal Accountant; adjust the PPE accounts in the books as necessary; prepare and submit the corresponding report together with the established subsidiary ledger for each class of PPE;
Require the Chairman of the Inventory Committee, in coordination with the Municipal General Services Officer and Municipal Engineer to complete and submit the Inventory of all Local Roads and Road Map and Local Road Network Property Cards, Report on Local Road Network of the Municipality as shown in Annex A of COA Circular No. 2015-008. The preparation of the Report of Local Road Network must be observed yearly. Also, keep and maintain the Local Road Network Property/Property Ledger Card for all roads and its components; and
Through the Municipal Accountant provide a full and appropriate disclosure of the PPE account in the Notes to Financial Statements as prescribed in the IPSAS.

